Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Isham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): habitational name from Isham, Northamptonshire. See   Isom  , compare   Esham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Esham","meanings":["English: variant of   Isham  . This surname is no longer found in Britain.","History: The name is first recorded in Northamton County, VA, when Daniel Esham came over as an indentured servant in 1651."]},{"name":"Isom","meanings":["English (Essex): habitational name from Isham in Northamptonshire. The placename is derived from the river name <i>Ise</i> (of Celtic origin) + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’."]},{"name":"Ishman","meanings":["English: possibly an altered form of   Isham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord Robert De Isham was born in 1380, in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Thomas De Isham. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1425, in his hometown, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1380–1425":"1380–1425","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–1425":"1380–1425","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1380–1425":"1380–1425","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lord Robert De Isham est né en 1380, à Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Thomas De Isham. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1425, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 45 ans."},"de":{"1380–1425":"1380–1425","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1350–Male":"1350–Verstorben","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Lord Robert De Isham wurde 1380 in Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, als Sohn von Thomas De Isham geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1425 im Alter von 45 Jahren in seinem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1380–1425":"1380–1425","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1350–Male":"1350–Desede","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Angletè, United Kingdom"},"hu":{"1380–1425":"1380–1425","1410–1461":"1410–1461","1350–Male":"1350–elhunyt","1425":"1425","1410":"1410","1461":"1461","1350":"1350","1380":"1380","Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Northamptonshire, Anglia, United Kingdom"